The '''Brenner Base Tunnel''' ({{langx|de|Brennerbasistunnel}}; {{langx|it|Galleria di base del Brennero}}) is a {{convert|55|km|mi|0|adj=mid|-long}} [[railway tunnel]] under construction through the base of the [[Eastern Alps]] beneath the [[Brenner Pass]]. Once completed, the Brenner Base Tunnel will rank as either the second or third [[List of longest tunnels|longest railway tunnel in the world]], depending on the definition employed. It will be surpassed in length only by the [[Gotthard Base Tunnel]] in Switzerland and, depending on the relative completion dates of these projects, the [[Mont d'Ambin Base Tunnel]] between France and Italy. When combined with the [[Inntal Tunnel]], which forms part of the existing [[Innsbruck bypass]], the Brenner Base Tunnel will reach a length of {{convert|64|km}}, making it the longest underground railway connection in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbt-se.com/en/did-you-know/ |title=Did you know … |website=BBT-SE.com |access-date=2016-02-01 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202005914/http://www.bbt-se.com/en/did-you-know/ |archive-date=2 February 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.tunnel-online.info/en/artikel/tunnel_Start_of_works_on_the_main_tunnel_2323530.html | title=BBT: Start of Works on the main Tunnel – tunnel | access-date=7 December 2019 | archive-date=31 October 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201031081602/https://www.tunnel-online.info/en/artikel/tunnel_Start_of_works_on_the_main_tunnel_2323530.html | url-status=live }}</ref>

It will run from near [[Innsbruck]], in [[Austria]], to [[Franzensfeste|Franzensfeste/Fortezza]], in [[Italy]], replacing part of the current [[Brenner railway]].<ref name="urlgetzner_2010-09">{{cite web
|url=http://www.getzner.com/fileadmin/data/upload/referenzen/case_studies/bahn/en/98-Getzner-Case-Study-Zulaufstrecke-Nord-Brenner-en.pdf
|title=Case Study: Northern Approach Line to the Brenner Base Tunnel
|date=September 2010
|publisher=getzner
|pages=4
|accessdate=2014-01-08
}}</ref> The line is part of [[Berlin–Palermo railway axis|Line 1]], the Berlin to Palermo route, of [[Trans-European Transport Networks]] (TEN-T) and funded by Austria and Italy with large contributions by the [[European Union]]. The tunnel is scheduled to be completed in 2032.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.railjournal.com/infrastructure/governors-protest-latest-delay-to-brenner-base-tunnel-construction/ |title=Governors protest latest delay to Brenner Base Tunnel construction |last=Fender |first=Keith |date=2021-05-27 |df=dmy-all |publisher=[[International Railway Journal]] |access-date=2021-08-23 |archive-date=2022-02-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220201231411/https://www.railjournal.com/infrastructure/governors-protest-latest-delay-to-brenner-base-tunnel-construction/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>Brenner Base Tunnel Delayed ''[[Modern Railways]]'' issue 874 July 2021 page 80</ref>

The [[Brenner Pass]], in the Alps at the border between Austria and Italy, is one of the most important traffic connections between northern and southern [[Europe]], and the motorway going over it is infamous for its frequent traffic jams.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/brenner-pass-austria-italy-spat-disrupts-berlaymonts-summer-break/ |title=Trucking hell in Tyrol |last=Cokelaere |first=Hanne |date=August 5, 2019 |website=Politico |access-date=22 October 2020 |archive-date=22 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201022060547/https://www.politico.eu/article/brenner-pass-austria-italy-spat-disrupts-berlaymonts-summer-break/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Pollution from transit traffic is a major concern because of the combination of [[Inversion (meteorology)|temperature inversion]] with the narrow shape of the valleys leading to the pass.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=de Franceschi |first1=M. |last2=Zardi |first2=D. |date=March 2009 |title=Study of wintertime high pollution episodes during the Brenner-South ALPNAP measurement campaign |journal=Meteorol Atmos Phys |volume=103 |issue=1–4 |pages=237–250 |doi=10.1007/s00703-008-0327-2 |bibcode=2009MAP...103..237D |s2cid=120275169 |issn=1436-5065}}</ref>

The goal is to relieve this situation by greatly improving the railway connection between [[Germany]] and [[Italy]] with the new tunnel, which will allow trains to cross the Alps much faster. Currently, speeds in the Brenner region barely exceed {{convert|70|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} due to the steepness of the existing tracks, which cross the pass at an elevation of {{Convert|1,371|m||abbr=}} above sea level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.tuttotreno.it/24565-ferrovia-del-brennero-150-anni-fa-i-primi-treni/|title=Ferrovia del Brennero, 150 anni fa i primi treni|last=Bruzzo|first=Marco|date=18 August 2017|website=Tutto Treno Blog|language=it|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209063117/http://blog.tuttotreno.it/24565-ferrovia-del-brennero-150-anni-fa-i-primi-treni/|archive-date=9 February 2018}}</ref>

The travel time from [[Innsbruck]] to [[Bolzano]] will be reduced from current 2 hours to just 50 minutes.<ref name=sdz>
