==Background==

The passenger and freight traffic across the Alps has increased greatly in recent years and further growth is forecast.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pompigna |first1=Andrea |last2=Mauro |first2=Raffaele |date=June 2020 |title=Input/Output models for freight transport demand: a macro approach to traffic analysis for a freight corridor |journal=Archives of Transport |volume=54 |issue=2 |pages=21–42 |doi=10.5604/01.3001.0014.2729 |bibcode=2020ArTr...54...21P |issn=2300-8830|doi-access=free }}</ref> Austria is a key country in movement of freight between northern and southern Europe and between eastern and western Europe. The Brenner region is very politically sensitive with respect to both local and cross-border transport issues. Between 1970 and 1999, highway freight increased seven-fold. (3 million to 22 million tonnes)
In 1990, 70% of the freight from eastern Europe was transported by rail and the remainder by trucks. These proportions were expected to reverse by 2010.<ref name="EU Policy 2004">{{Google books|kspRHY8UfX0C|Contemporary Issues and Debates in EU Policy: The European Union and ...|page=PA182 ff}} {{ISBN|071906418X}}</ref>{{rp|182ff}}
About three-quarters of traffic through the Brenner Pass is currently carried by road transport. Local residents have long fought for relief from the associated pollution. The construction of a rail tunnel is considered by its proponents to be necessary for a shift of freight traffic from road to rail.

The railway line from [[Innsbruck]] in [[North Tyrol]] to [[Bolzano]] in [[South Tyrol]] was built between 1860 and 1867. Tight curve radii and gradients of up to 2.6% complicate rail operations. However, improvements on the Italian side in recent years to the existing line, which were completed in late 2008, allow the line theoretically to accommodate 240 trains per day. The grades were not significantly improved.

The new Brenner line would have a maximum gradient of 0.4%-0.7%. Thus, a locomotive would be capable of hauling more than double the weight. The new line (the [[base tunnel]] together with the southern approach from [[Waidbruck|Waidbruck/Ponte Gardena]] to [[Franzensfeste|Franzensfeste/Fortezza]]) would cut travel time between Innsbruck and Bolzano from about two hours today to less than half that.

==Project==

===Main tunnel===
The {{convert|55|km||abbr=|adj=on}} long, twin-tube tunnel begins in the Innsbruck suburb of Wilten and penetrates the [[Alps]] reaching a height of about {{convert|840|m}} above sea level (ASL). The tunnel will be up to {{convert|1720|m|abbr=on}} below the surface at its deepest point in the [[gneiss]] section stretching south from the Italian border<!--Staatsgrenze-->.<ref name="urlwww.tunneltalk.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.tunneltalk.com/Brenner-Base-Tunnel-Feb11-A-leap-forward.php|title=Brenner project takes a major leap forward|last=Reynolds|first=Patrick|date=February 2011|website=Tunnel Talk|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820150827/http://tunneltalk.com/Brenner-Base-Tunnel-Feb11-A-leap-forward.php|archive-date=2013-08-20|accessdate=2013-08-14}}</ref> Since under the most recent plan the tunnel starts as a twin-tube tunnel, the junction already prepared in the [[Inntal Tunnel|Inntal tunnel]] on the [[Innsbruck bypass]] will not be used. Instead, a diversion with several branches is planned.{{citation needed|date=June 2020}}

The volume of rock to be excavated during the construction of the tunnel is estimated at {{Convert|21|e6m3||abbr=off}}, of which approximately 60% will be incurred in Austria, as about 60% of the tunnel will be in Austria. A part of the spoil will be used as [[Fill dirt|fill]] for the approach lines and another part of the spoil material is used to produce the concrete segment for the final lining of the tunnel. The main tunnels will have a circular cross section with a diameter of approx. {{Convert|8.1|m||abbr=on}}.

According to current planning the apex of the tunnel will be at the border at an altitude of about {{convert|810|m|abbr=on}} ASL, although an apex farther south would have been lower. The placing of the apex at the border is set out in the treaty between Austria and Italy. As justification for this choice it is stated that this will allow Austrian water to run in the tunnel to Austria and Italian water to Italy.

===Northern approach===
On its north end, the base tunnel (BBT) has two entrances, which must go underground a few kilometres before the junction with the main tunnels, and will also be built as part of the BBT. One route leads from the main Innsbruck station under [[Bergisel]] and the other connects with the Innsbruck bypass. This route adds about {{convert|8|km}} more to the length of the tunnel than the Innsbruck station route; with it included, the BBT, at {{convert|62.7|km}}, would become the longest continuous railroad tunnel in the world. However, if the Axentunnel extension is added to the [[Gotthard Base Tunnel]], its length would become {{convert|75|km}}, allowing it to reclaim the 'longest tunnel' title.

The northern approach from Munich within Germany is the {{convert|165|km}} [[Munich–Rosenheim railway|Grafing]]–[[Rosenheim–Kufstein railway|Rosenheim–Kufstein]] route.  The "Brenner Nordzulauf" (Brenner northern link) project aims to construct a high-speed line for speeds of up to 230&nbsp;km/h (143&nbsp;mph) between [[Grafing]] and [[Brannenburg]] in addition to the existing line, adapting the route's capacity to the projected increase as a result of the BBT. The project has reached in-depth planning stages but suffers from lacking support by locals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brennernordzulauf.eu/aktuelles.html|title=Aktuelles - Brenner-Nordzulauf|website=www.brennernordzulauf.eu|access-date=2019-04-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410135950/https://www.brennernordzulauf.eu/aktuelles.html|archive-date=2019-04-10|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Full citation needed|date=March 2020}} A more direct route between Munich and Innsbruck, for example, via [[Garmisch-Partenkirchen]], [[Mittenwald]] and [[Seefeld, Tirol|Seefeld]] was not pursued, though it could have shortened the Munich Innsbruck line to {{convert|129|km}}.

In Austria, a [[New Lower Inn Valley railway|new double-track high-speed line]] supplements the [[Lower Inn Valley railway]] between [[Wörgl]] and [[Baumkirchen]]. It manages to cut travel time between Munich and Innsbruck from 1:50 via the old tracks to merely 0:55 using the high-speed line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beg.co.at/fileadmin/downloads/Beg_AMA.pdf|title=Die Neue Unterinntalbahn auf höchstem Niveau Kundl-Baumkirchen|date=October 2007|website=BEG|language=de|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808034817/https://www.beg.co.at/fileadmin/downloads/Beg_AMA.pdf|archive-date=2017-08-08|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> About {{convert|32|km}} of the {{convert|40|km||abbr=|adj=on}} line through the [[Lower Inn Valley]] (''Unterinntal'') is built underground, in troughs, or under snow sheds. Noise and vibration mitigation is accomplished by the use of {{convert|80000|m2}} of elastomer in a [[Effective mass (spring-mass system)|mass-spring]] system. The segment's track superstructure is load class E5. It is capable of handling 260–300 trains per day.<ref name="urlgetzner_2010-09" /> This section was opened on 9 December 2012.<ref name="urlobb_2012-11">{{cite web|url=http://konzern.oebb.at/de/Presse/Presseinformationen_aus_den_Bundeslaendern/Tirol/PDF/2012/Q4/2012_11_26_PI_Infra_Tirol_Unterinntal_final.pdf|title=Neue Unterinntalbahn: Highspeed und höchste Sicherheit|date=2012-11-26|publisher=ÖBB-holding AG|pages=3|language=de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930170147/http://konzern.oebb.at/de/Presse/Presseinformationen_aus_den_Bundeslaendern/Tirol/PDF/2012/Q4/2012_11_26_PI_Infra_Tirol_Unterinntal_final.pdf|archive-date=2013-09-30|accessdate=2014-01-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> Planning is under way on the continuation of this line to the German border at Brannenburg.

===Southern approach===
On the south end, the base tunnel will be connected to a {{convert|180|km}} new line all the way to [[Verona]] with junctions with the old railway and no stations (similarly to the Neue Unterinntalbahn). Planning of the new line started around 2000 and the project was divided in seven, later eight, sections mostly underground (about 90%); first route plans of the new railway were approved in 2009.<ref name="silosIT">{{cite web|url=https://silos.infrastrutturestrategiche.it/Home/Scheda/1406|title=SILOS: Sistema Informativo Legge Opere Strategiche - Direttrice Brennero-Verona-Bologna / Tratta di valico e tratta di adduzione - Potenziamento linea Fortezza-Verona|publisher=[[Chamber of Deputies (Italy)]]|language=it|accessdate=2026-01-16}}</ref> {{As of|2026}} two sections are already under construction with three more deemed "high priority" for their role in routing traffic to the new base tunnel; other three sections were assessed not critical for the base tunnel operations.<ref name="fsQuad">{{cite web|url=https://www.fsitaliane.it/it/opere-strategiche/brennero-e-linea-fortezza-verona.html|title=Brennero e Fortezza-Verona|publisher=[[Ferrovie dello Stato]]|language=it|accessdate=2026-01-16}}</ref>

The construction lots are (status {{as of|January 2026|lc=y}}):<ref name="rfiLotto3A">{{cite web|url=https://www.mit.gov.it/nfsmitgov/files/media/basic/2021-10/21.10.22_Circonvallazione%20Trento_CSLLPP_revA.pdf|title=Lotto 3A: Circonvallazione di Trento - Progetto di fattibilità tecnico economica|date=2021-10-22|publisher=Italferr [[Rete Ferroviaria Italiana|RFI]]|language=it|accessdate=2026-01-16}}</ref><ref name="rfiLotto4">{{cite web|url=https://www.rfi.it/content/dam/rfi/rete/opere-sottoposte-a-dibattito-pubblico/lotto-4-ingresso-verona-da-nord/Relazione_di_Progetto_lotto4.pdf |title=Lotto 4 - Ingresso a Verona da Nord - Relazione di Progetto|publisher=Italferr [[Rete Ferroviaria Italiana|RFI]]|language=it|accessdate=2026-01-16}}</ref>
