==History==
The Brenner tunnel is the most important link in the [[Berlin–Palermo railway axis]], a series of projects that will create a single railway line from [[Berlin]] in [[Germany]] to [[Palermo]] in [[Sicily]]. In April 2003, the governments of Austria and Italy signed an agreement to build the tunnel.<ref>Brenner Base Tunnel Agreement ''[[International Railway Journal]]'' May 2003 page 2</ref>

===Schedule history===
Early in the preliminary planning, at a Brussels meeting in June 2005, BBT SE (Brenner Base Tunnel Societas Europae), presented an interim status report. Expectations following the meeting were that the project could be finalized and the pilot tunnel started by 2006. The target for the tunnel to start service was 2015.<ref name="urlwww.infrasite.nl">{{cite web|url=http://www.infrasite.nl/news/news_articles.php?ID_nieuwsberichten=2448|title=EC welcomes progress - Brenner Base tunnel project|date=24 June 2005|website=Infrasite.nl|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304070342/http://www.infrasite.nl/news/news_articles.php?ID_nieuwsberichten=2448|archive-date=4 March 2016|accessdate=2013-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release|title=Commission welcomes progress of Brenner Base tunnel project|date=23 June 2005|publisher=European Commission|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-05-781_en.htm?locale=en|access-date=2013-08-06}}</ref>

In 2007 a construction timeline with a 2022 finish date was specified in a memorandum signed by the Austrian and Italian ministers of transport.<ref name="KVM 2007-0910">{{cite web|url= http://ec.europa.eu/ten/transport/coordinators/doc/2006_2007/2007_09_10_pp01_en.pdf|title= Annual activity report by the coordinator Karel Van Miert - PRIORITY PROJECT 1 Berlin-Verona/Milan-Bologna-Naples-Messina-Palermo rail link|accessdate= 2007-12-09|last= van Miert|first= Karel|author-link= Karel Van Miert|date= 2007-09-10|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080228033203/http://ec.europa.eu/ten/transport/coordinators/doc/2006_2007/2007_09_10_pp01_en.pdf|archive-date= 2008-02-28|url-status= live}}</ref>

===Funding history===
In December 2008 [[Antonio Tajani]], the European commissioner for transport, approved funds totalling €1.7 billion to finance 11 railway projects that together should establish two major routes across the continent.<ref>{{cite press release|title= Brenner Tunnel: construction of the exploratory gallery begins|publisher= [[European Commission]]|date= 2006-06-29|url= http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=IP/06/880&format=HTML&aged=1&language=EN&guiLanguage=en|accessdate= 2006-12-13|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090831182822/http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=IP%2F06%2F880&format=HTML&aged=1&language=EN&guiLanguage=en|archive-date= 2009-08-31|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/ten-t-rail-funding-signed.html|title=TEN-T rail funding signed|date=5 December 2008|website=[[Railway Gazette International]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110212012736/http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/ten-t-rail-funding-signed.html|archive-date=12 February 2011|accessdate=2010-10-18}}</ref>

In May 2009 it was confirmed that final go-ahead for the project had been given.<ref name="BBTapproved">{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/brenner-base-tunnel-approved.html|title=Brenner base tunnel approved|date=11 May 2009|website=Railway Gazette International|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110212012703/http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/brenner-base-tunnel-approved.html|archive-date=12 February 2011|accessdate=2010-10-18}}</ref>

The final estimated cost was put at €8.384 billion at 2018 levels.<ref name="KVM 2007-0910"/>

===Construction history===
In the summer of 2007 work started on a pilot tunnel to run along the line of the future tunnel and to be used for removing water and spoil during the major construction phase. Construction of the pilot tunnel between 2006 and 2009 was estimated to cost €430 million and would be 50% EU funded.

On 6 July 2019, two Austrian segments were connected, and an unbroken {{convert|36|km}} long tunnel was formed – around 65% of the tunnel's {{convert|55|km}} projected length.<ref name=expl>{{Cite web|url=https://www.railjournal.com/infrastructure/contractors-celebrate-brenner-exploratory-tunnel-breakthrough/|title=Contractors celebrate Brenner exploratory tunnel breakthrough|date=10 July 2020|access-date=14 October 2020|archive-date=1 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201001110733/https://www.railjournal.com/infrastructure/contractors-celebrate-brenner-exploratory-tunnel-breakthrough/|url-status=live}}</ref> On 18 September 2025 for the first time the two tunnel sections, from Italy and from Austria, were joined underground by the break-through of the exploratory tunnel.<ref>{{cite news | work=Reuters | date= 18 September 2025|  title=Contractors celebrate Brenner exploratory tunnel breakthrough |  url=https://www.reuters.com/world/historic-tunnel-created-under-alps-connect-italy-austria-2025-09-18/|access-date=12 October 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite news  | work= Engineering News Record  | date= 22 September 2025  | title= Major Breakthrough for Brenner Base Tunnel Through the Alps  | first= Jeff  | last= Rubenstone  | url= https://www.enr.com/articles/61407-major-breakthrough-for-brenner-base-tunnel-through-the-alps  | access-date= 12 October 2025  | archive-date= 9 October 2025  | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20251009135219/https://www.enr.com/articles/61407-major-breakthrough-for-brenner-base-tunnel-through-the-alps  | url-status= live  }}</ref> The exploratory tunnel runs 12{{nbsp}}metres below where the final tunnel will be bored and it will be used for drainage and maintenance after the rail connection opens.<ref name=expl/>

As of March 2025, at least three workers died while working on the tunnel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.derstandard.at/story/3000000221087/41-jaehriger-bei-arbeiten-fuer-tiroler-brennerbasistunnel-getoetet|title=41-year-old killed while working for the Brenner Base Tunnel (German)|date=22 May 2024|access-date=18 December 2024|archive-date=29 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240629110451/https://www.derstandard.at/story/3000000221087/41-jaehriger-bei-arbeiten-fuer-tiroler-brennerbasistunnel-getoetet|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.derstandard.at/story/3000000263566/arbeiter-bei-unfall-auf-brennerbasistunnel-baustelle-get246tet|title=Workers killed in Brenner-based accident tunnel construction site|access-date=3 April 2025|archive-date=30 March 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250330162538/https://www.derstandard.at/story/3000000263566/arbeiter-bei-unfall-auf-brennerbasistunnel-baustelle-get246tet|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Design==
The final design will consist of two tunnels, {{convert|55|km}} long. A centre tunnel {{convert|12|m}} below the two primary tunnels will be used during construction as a guide tunnel to determine geological conditions, and later for drainage and emergency access. There will be a cross over between the tunnels every {{convert|333|m|ft}}.  Multi-function stations will be located at Trens (in [[Freienfeld]]), St. Jodok, and a third station towards the northern end of the tunnel to provide operational and emergency services. [[European Train Control System|ETCS]] Level 2 will be installed to provide train control.<ref name="BBTapproved"/>

==Funding==
As the transalpine stretch of the SCAN-MED Corridor, the Brenner Base Tunnel receives substantial funding from the European Union. Between 2015 and 2023, 50% of the costs for the exploratory tunnel (about 330 million Euro) and 40% of the costs for the two main tunnels (about 880 million Euro) were covered by the EU. Austria and Italy will each cover half of the remaining costs.

The 2017 estimate of the basic costs for the Brenner Base Tunnel was 7.8 billion Euro. Considering the planned end date for the project (2028), the estimate total costs, with risk provision and adjustment for inflation are about 8.384 billion Euro. They can be divided into 4 large categories: 60% of the cost comes from the engineering works, 15% is for outfitting, 10% is for planning, services and internal costs, 1% for parcels of land and related issues and 14% for risk provision.<ref>{{cite web |title=Funding |url=https://www.bbt-se.com/en/tunnel/funding/ |website=Brenner Base Tunnel |publisher=BBT SE |accessdate=17 August 2020 |archive-date=27 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200927132232/https://www.bbt-se.com/en/tunnel/funding/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

